SIMPLE: monogenesis
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Monogenesis
<hw>Mon`o*gen"e*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>genesis</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Oneness of origin; esp. <fld>(Biol.)</fld>, development of all
beings in the universe from a single cell; -- opposed to
<contr>polygenesis</contr>. Called also <altname>monism</altname>.</def>
<rj><au>Dana.</au> <au>Haeckel.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>That form of reproduction which
requires but one parent, as in reproduction by fission or in the
formation of buds, etc., which drop off and form new individuals;
asexual reproduction.</def> <rj><au>Haeckel.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The direct development of an
embryo, without metamorphosis, into an organism similar to the parent
organism; -- opposed to <contr>metagenesis</contr>.</def> <rj><au>E. van
Beneden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogenetic</ent>⟦br⟧
